div.p:
—through the NSCIC, determine by December 1,
                    1973 which national intelligence products satisfy user needs and identify new
                    product requirements;

—review the USIB committee structure before the
                    end of 1973 and direct, if necessary, changes to increase USIB effectiveness in advising me on national
                    requirements;

—instruct the Council to review all R&D
                    activities within the National Intelligence Program to identify ongoing R&D efforts, their costs, their purpose, and
                    who has responsibility for each effort;

—undertake specific studies to evaluate the intelligence product and its worth to
                    the consumer and eliminate intelligence collection and production effort of
                    marginal usefulness;

—undertake selective review during the next 18 months of the following in order
                    to better rationalize the division of labor and increase the number of services
                    of common concern performed within the community;

—have the Department of Defense identify by November 1, 1973 the ten or so
                    highest priority needs in the field of technical intelligence required by their
                    planners;

—in coordination with other Federal agencies, identify the needs for foreign
                    intelligence in these areas, and match the unique capabilities of the
                    intelligence community to those needs;
